First of all a working solution: The DER encoded X.509/SPKI key generated with `Key#getEncoded()` is Base64 encoded and then imported to the JavaScript side as follows:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    (async () =&gt; {
        const subtle = window.crypto.subtle;
        var keyAB = b642ab(&quot;&quot;)

        var key = await subtle.importKey(&quot;spki&quot;, new Uint8Array(keyAB), { name: &quot;RSA-OAEP&quot;, hash: &quot;SHA-256&quot; }, false, [ &quot;encrypt&quot; ])   
        console.log(key)
    })();

    function b642ab(base64string){
        return Uint8Array.from(atob(base64string), c =&gt; c.charCodeAt(0)).buffer;
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The problem is caused by the `Int32Array` type you used. A typed array is an array-like view of an underlying `ArrayBuffer`. In an `Int32Array` each element corresponds to 4 bytes.&lt;br&gt;Since your `Int32Array` contains the *same* values as your `Key#getEncoded()`, the underlying `ArrayBuffer` contains 4 times as many values and therefore no longer corresponds to the original key.

